# Void Dominion — public HTTPS/WSS via Caddy (HTTPS-2.1). Caddy terminates TLS in front
# of the game server, which itself never binds a public port.
#
# Used with the TLS overlay (see deploy/docker-compose.tls.yml):
#
#   DOMAIN=play.example.com SERVER_BIND=127.0.0.1 \
#     docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.tls.yml up -d --build
#
# DNS PREREQUISITE: point DOMAIN's A/AAAA record at THIS host first. Caddy proves
# ownership over :80/:443 (ACME HTTP-01 / TLS-ALPN-01) before Let's Encrypt issues the
# certificate — without working DNS the handshake for a cert cannot complete.
#
# What Caddy does out of the box, so this file stays tiny:
#   * provisions AND auto-renews a Let's Encrypt cert for {$DOMAIN} (covers HTTPS-2.2 —
#     renewal is automatic; certs persist in the caddy-data volume across restarts);
#   * redirects http:// -> https:// and serves HTTP/3;
#   * upgrades WebSocket transparently, so wss://{$DOMAIN}/matches/... just works;
#   * sets X-Forwarded-Proto / -Host / -For on the upstream request — the server trusts
#     these ONLY behind a proxy (TRUST_PROXY=1, HTTPS-1.1) to see the real scheme/host.
#
# The upstream is reached over the compose network at server:8788; the plain HTTP port
# stays on loopback (HTTPS-2.1 DoD: no direct plain-port exposure to the internet).
#
# TESTING WITHOUT A REAL DOMAIN / CERT:
#   * self-signed:  set `tls internal` inside the site block (Caddy's local CA);
#   * ACME staging: add a global `{ acme_ca https://acme-staging-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory }`
#     block to avoid Let's Encrypt production rate limits while iterating (HTTPS-2.2).

{$DOMAIN} {
	encode zstd gzip
	reverse_proxy server:8788
}
